  lower_bound: Inclusive(1000),
  upper_bound: Exclusive(2000)
}
```

The difference matters: with `Inclusive(1000)`, transaction time 1000 is valid; with `Exclusive(1000)`, it is not. This precision is crucial for smart contracts where exact timing constraints are needed.

IntervalBoundType is used to define the boundaries of time intervals in Aiken. It typically has two cases: Finite (representing a specific timestamp in milliseconds or seconds) and Infinite (representing an unbounded boundary).

Here's a practical example of creating a time window:

```aiken
use aiken.interval.{Finite, Infinite, IntervalBoundType}

fn validate_transaction_time(lower_bound: IntervalBoundType, upper_bound: IntervalBoundType) -> Bool {
  // Check if bounds are properly defined
  let is_lower_finite = case lower_bound {
    Finite(time) -> time > 0
    Infinite -> True
  }

  let is_upper_finite = case upper_bound {
    Finite(time) -> time > 0
    Infinite -> True
  }

  is_lower_finite && is_upper_finite
}
```

This validates that a transaction's time interval has properly defined bounds, where Finite holds a specific timestamp and Infinite represents no upper or lower limit. Use this when you need to enforce time constraints on when a smart contract action can be executed.

IntervalBoundType te permite definir los límites de una ventana de tiempo en Aiken. Puedes usarlo para especificar cuándo una transacción es válida en la blockchain.

Aquí tienes un ejemplo práctico:

