You can validate a new protocol version proposal using the `new_version` field from the governance module. Here's a practical example:

```aiken
use cardano/governance

pub fn validate_protocol_upgrade(current_version: ProtocolVersion, proposed: ProtocolVersion) -> Bool {
  // Check if major version is incremented correctly
  if proposed.major > current_version.major {
    // Major can only increment by exactly 1
    proposed.major == current_version.major + 1 &&
    // Minor must reset to 0 when major increments
    proposed.minor == 0
  } else if proposed.major == current_version.major {
    // Same major: minor can increment by 1
    proposed.minor == current_version.minor + 1
  } else {
    // Cannot decrement major or minor
    False
  }
}
```

This validator ensures the proposed `new_version` follows all the rules: major increments by exactly 1 (and resets minor to 0), minor increments by exactly 1 (when major unchanged), and neither can be decremented. Use this in a governance validator script to enforce version upgrade constraints before accepting protocol changes.

Para verificar que una propuesta de `new_version` es válida, debes crear un validador que compruebe todas las reglas de versionado. Aquí te muestro cómo:

```aiken
use cardano/governance

pub fn check_version_proposal(current: ProtocolVersion, proposed: ProtocolVersion) -> Bool {
  let major_valid = if proposed.major > current.major {
    proposed.major == current.major + 1 && proposed.minor == 0
  } else {
    proposed.major == current.major
  }

  let minor_valid = if proposed.major == current.major {
    proposed.minor == current.minor + 1
  } else {
    True // minor ya fue validado en la rama anterior
  }

  major_valid && minor_valid
}
```

**Las reglas que debes verificar:**
- Si incrementa `major`: debe ser exactamente +1, y `minor` debe ser 0
- Si `major` no cambia: `minor` solo puede incrementar en 1
- Nunca pueden decrementar

