The gift card validator uses two parameters to guarantee uniqueness and prevent double-minting:

```aiken
validator gift_card(token_name: ByteArray, utxo_ref: OutputReference) {
  spend (_d, _r, own_ref: OutputReference, transaction: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // The validator ensures the UTxO being spent matches utxo_ref
    // This guarantees the contract can only run once (one-shot)
    own_ref == utxo_ref
  }
}
```

**Parameters explained:**
- `token_name: ByteArray` - The name of the NFT being minted. This is baked into the compiled validator, so different gift card instances use different validators with different token names.
- `utxo_ref: OutputReference` - A specific UTxO (transaction ID + output index) that must be spent. Since UTxOs are unique and can only be spent once, this guarantees the validator executes exactly once.

**Why this works:**
Once the UTxO identified by `utxo_ref` is spent, it no longer exists on the blockchain. Any attempt to run the same validator again would fail because the UTxO is gone. This is a standard Cardano pattern for one-shot contracts—you tie the contract's execution to a specific, unique UTxO that can never be spent twice.

